{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486759"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:43:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:43:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"169"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"169","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/169"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.16,0.77,0.02,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"169"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50965"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"169","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/169"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"169"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36205"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"104"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4608"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"7864"},{"type":"tags","id":"9600"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12366"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12367"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12394"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42012"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44890"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50965","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50965"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department after being retrieved from a motor vehicle crash in which she sustained steering wheel injuries. She is experiencing chest pain and dyspnoea. She is able to recall the events leading up to the crash and speaks in clear sentences. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 136/min, blood pressure 84/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 26/min, SpO2 95% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. She is pale and diaphoretic. Her central capillary refill time is three seconds, her jugular venous pressure is elevated and her extremities are cool to touch. On auscultation of the chest, air entry is equal bilaterally and heart sounds are muffled. An ECG shows sinus tachycardia with low voltage QRS complexes and electrical alternans.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence noradrenaline infusion","One litre bolus of isotonic saline","Ultrasound-guided pericardiocentesis","Intercostal catheter insertion","High flow oxygen"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs and symptoms consistent with cardiac tamponade, likely due to blunt chest trauma from the motor vehicle crash. The clinical picture is strongly suggestive of Beck\u0027s triad (hypotension, elevated jugular venous pressure, and muffled heart sounds) along with chest pain, dyspnoea, tachypnoea, tachycardia, and characteristic ECG findings of electrical alternans.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound-guided pericardiocentesis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management for this haemodynamically unstable patient with cardiac tamponade. Urgent decompression of the pericardial sac is crucial to enable ventricular filling and facilitate a return to adequate cardiac output. Ultrasound guidance has been shown to have lower complication and mortality rates and higher success rates compared to \u0027blind\u0027 pericardiocentesis. This approach also allows for radiological confirmation of the diagnosis, although cardiac tamponade remains primarily a clinical diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eone litre bolus of isotonic saline\u003C/strong\u003E might temporarily improve preload and cardiac output, but it does not address the underlying problem of cardiac compression. In cardiac tamponade, fluid resuscitation alone is often ineffective and may worsen the situation by increasing pericardial fluid accumulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing noradrenaline infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as the primary issue is mechanical obstruction to cardiac filling, not vasodilation. Increasing systemic vascular resistance with vasopressors may actually worsen cardiac output in tamponade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntercostal catheter insertion\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for a pneumothorax or haemothorax, but there are no clinical findings suggestive of these conditions. The patient has equal air entry bilaterally, and her symptoms are more consistent with cardiac tamponade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh flow oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E may provide some symptomatic relief for dyspnoea, but it does not address the underlying cause of the patient\u0027s haemodynamic instability. While oxygen therapy may be provided as supportive care, it should not delay definitive treatment with pericardiocentesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter pericardiocentesis, the patient will require close monitoring, likely in an intensive care setting. Further investigations such as echocardiography and chest CT may be needed to identify the cause and extent of cardiac injury. Depending on the findings, cardiothoracic surgical consultation may be necessary for definitive management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["In the context of a chest injury, the finding of electrical alternans implies cardiac tamponade.","Urgent pericardiocentesis is the definitive treatment for cardiac tamponade with haemodynamic instability."],"references":["De Carlini, CC \u0026 Maggiolini, S 2017, \u2018Pericardiocentesis in cardiac tamponade: indications and practical aspects\u2019, European Society of Cardiology, vol. 15, no. 19, viewed 7 April 2020, \u003Chttps://www.escardio.org/Journals/E-Journal-of-Cardiology-Practice/Volume-15/Pericardiocentesis-in-cardiac-tamponade-indications-and-practical-aspects\u003E.","Heffner, AC 2019, Emergency pericardiocentesis, UpToDate, viewed 11 June 2020, \u003Chttps://www-uptodate-com.proxy.library.adelaide.edu.au/contents/emergency-pericardiocentesis?search=cardiac%20tamponade\u0026topicRef=4921\u0026source=related_link#H800834\u003E.","Ingram, D \u0026 Strecker-McGraw, MK 2020, Electrical Alternans, PubMed, StatPearls Publishing, Treasure Island (FL), viewed 7 April 2020, \u003Chttps://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534229/\u003E.","Jensen, JK, Hvitfeldt Poulsen, S \u0026 M\u00f8lgaard, H 2017, \u2018Cardiac tamponade: a clinical challenge\u2019, European Society of Cardiology, vol. 15, no. 1, viewed 11 June 2020, \u003Chttps://www.escardio.org/Journals/E-Journal-of-Cardiology-Practice/Volume-15/Cardiac-tamponade-a-clinical-challenge\u003E."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36205"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"169"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36205","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36205"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-19T19:49:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-19T19:52:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"169"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50965"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","lin